ome characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Faye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Fay  .","French: variant of   Fay   3 or a habitational name from (La) Faye, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Faille   1 and   Lafaye  .","West African (mainly Senegal): from the name of the Faye clan of the Serer people, of unexplained etymology. This surname is also found among the Lebou people. Compare   Fye   3 and   Paye   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Faille","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Agathe, Andre.","Altered form of French   Faye  . Compare   Fayette   1 and   Foy   5.","French: metonymic occupational name for a torchbearer, from Old French <i>faille</i> ‘torch’ (from Late Latin <i>facilla</i>)."]},{"name":"Fay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, John Patrick, Donovan, Fergus, Kieran, Liam, Nuala.","English: nickname for a person believed to have supernatural qualities, from Middle English, Old French <i>faie</i> ‘fairy, witch’ (from Late Latin <i>fata</i> ‘fate, destiny’).","English: nickname for a trustworthy person, from Middle English, Old French <i>fei</i> ‘loyalty, trust’."]}]},{"name":"Aimery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Wiltshire, of Norman origin): variant of   Damery  , a habitational name from Daumeray (Maine-et-Loire), France."],"variants":[{"name":"Damery","meanings":["Danish, German: Celebrated soldier."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aimery V de Faye was born in 10